liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The secretary for the Australian Council of Trade Unions, Sally McManus, has welcomed the federal government's decision not to re-appoint Philip Lowe as the Reserve Bank governor. She says while Mr Lowe has served the country well, it provides an opportunity for a fresh look at how the central bank goes about its business. "There's been clearly mistakes made over the last couple of years and we're hoping that the new governor does take a new approach especially in the areas of wages and understanding how wages work as well as unemployment," she says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Unions welcome fresh appointment of new RBA governor

children.content: The secretary for the Australian Council of Trade Unions, Sally McManus, has welcomed the federal government's decision not to re-appoint Philip Lowe as the Reserve Bank governor.
She says while Mr Lowe has served the country well, it provides an opportunity for a fresh look at how the central bank goes about its business.

"There's been clearly mistakes made over the last couple of years and we're hoping that the new governor does take a new approach especially in the areas of wages and understanding how wages work as well as unemployment," she says.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: With Michele Bullock ready to step into Philip Lowe's (metaphorical) shoes, it's worth noting that it's not at all unusual to see a deputy RBA governor eventually being made governor. In fact, if history tells us anything, it's almost par for the course. I've had a (quick) deep dive into the RBA history books, and there have only been three governors who took on the top job without being deputy governor first. Those three are: Bernie Fraser, RBA governor from 1989 to 1996 Bob Johnston, RBA governor from 1982 to 1989 Herbert 'Nugget' Coombs, RBA governor from 1960 to 1962, then again from 1963 to 1968 That means five out of the past eight RBA governors have been deputy governor before taking on the top job — and now with Michele Bullock, that will make it six out of nine deputies going on to become governor.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: It's not uncommon for deputy RBA governors to take the top job

children.content: With Michele Bullock ready to step into Philip Lowe's (metaphorical) shoes, it's worth noting that it's not at all unusual to see a deputy RBA governor eventually being made governor.
In fact, if history tells us anything, it's almost par for the course.
I've had a (quick) deep dive into the RBA history books, and there have only been
three governors who took on the top job without being deputy governor
first.
Those three are:
Bernie Fraser
, RBA governor from 1989 to 1996
Bob Johnston
, RBA governor from 1982 to 1989
Herbert 'Nugget' Coombs
, RBA governor from 1960 to 1962, then again from 1963 to 1968

That means five out of the past eight RBA governors have been deputy governor before taking on the top job — and now with Michele Bullock, that will make it six out of nine deputies going on to become governor.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It might be a big day for the central bank, but you wouldn't know it from the outside. My colleague, business reporter Sue Lannin has spent her morning outside the RBA building in Martin Place in Sydney, and says unless you knew what was happening, you'd think it was any ordinary day. Here's what it's been like: "It was busy outside the RBA this morning but not because of the appointment at the first woman to lead the bank. "Members of the Falun Dafa religious group, which is outlawed by China, were protesting. "At one point during my live TV cross they started up with a brass band. "It was pretty quiet apart from that, aside from a few TV camera crews. "Michele Bullock is in Canberra and there was no sign of Philip Lowe."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Business as usual at the RBA offices in Sydney

children.content: It might be a big day for the central bank, but you wouldn't know it from the outside.
My colleague,
business reporter Sue Lannin
has spent her morning outside the RBA building in Martin Place in Sydney, and says unless you knew what was happening, you'd think it was any ordinary day.
Here's what it's been like:
"It was busy outside the RBA this morning but not because of the appointment at the first woman to lead the bank.
"Members of the Falun Dafa religious group, which is outlawed by China, were protesting.
"At one point during my live TV cross they started up with a brass band.
"It was pretty quiet apart from that, aside from a few TV camera crews.
"Michele Bullock is in Canberra and there was no sign of Philip Lowe."
